{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170975/1938011301/0021.xml":{"full_text":"NATIONAL NEWS\nCHEERED LOUDLY\nAT JACKSON DAY\nFETE AT CAPITAL\nPresident Promises \u2018Cheer\nful Fight\u2019 With Handful\nSeeking to Retain \u2018Auto\ncratic Controls\u2019\nWashington, Jan. 8 (AP)\nPresident Roosevelt gave notice to\nnight that he would wage a no\ncompromise fight against a minority\nof \u201cbusinessmen, bankers and in\ndustrialists.\u201d\nThat nfinority intends to make a\nstruggle \"to the last ditch to retain\nautocratic control\u201d over the coun\ntry\u2019s economy, the President charged\nin a Jackson day address to the\nnation.\nAt the same time, the chief\nexecutive pledged cooperation with\nall who were willing to \"help eradi\ncate the evils that flow from undue\nconcentration of economic power or\nunfair business practices.\u201d\nTo Fight \u201cThe Few\u201d Cheerfully\nThe President spoke at the annual\ndinner here of Democrats celebrating\nAndrew Jackson\u2019s victory in the battle\nof New Orleans. His words went by\nradio to similar Democratic dinners\nthroughout the land.\n\u25a0'The White House door is always\nopen to all our citizens who come of\nfering to help eradicate the evils that\nflow from undue concentration of\neconomic power or unfair business\npractices\u2014who offer to do all that is\npossible by cooperative endeavor and\nto aid in corrective and helpful legis\nlation where necessary,\u201d he said.\n\"We know that there will be a few\n\u2014a mere handful of the total of busi\nness men and bankers and industrial\nists\u2014who will fight to the last ditch\nto retain such autocratic controls over\nthe industry and the finances of the\ncountry as they now possess.\n\u201cWith this handful, it is going to\nbe a fight\u2014a cheerful fight on my\npart, but a fight in which there will\nbe no compromise with evil\u2014no let\nUp until the inevitable day of victory.\"\nPresident Applauded\nApplause greeted the President\u2019s\npromise of a no compromise battle.\nThe .President and Mrs Roosevelt\nwere given a standing ovation when\nthen arrived early in the flag-draped\nbanquet hall. Scores of guests had\nnot yet taken their seats.\nMr Roosevelt, in dinner .jacket, took\na seat between Vice-President Garner\nand Speaker Bankhead, while the first\nlady, in light blue gown, was escorted\nto a table occupied by Senator Bark\nley, the majority leader of the Senate:\nMrs J. Hamilton Lewis. Marvin H.\nMclntyre, presidential secretary: Mrs\nL. W. Robert, wife of the secretary\nof the Democratic national committee,\nand others.\nRobert sat at the speaker's table,\nas did Breckenridge Long, former em\nbassador to Italy, who presided as\nlocal committee chairman.\nMany Democrats Absent\nCabinet officers, senators and repre\nsentatives and their wives, and a few\nmen high in the business and finan\ncial world were in the audience.\nThe dinner, first big Democratic\nget-tbgethr-r since the party battle\nover the Roosevelt court bill, drew a\nsprinkling of senators who had op\nposed the chief executive on that\nissue\u2014but most of them stayed away.\nAmong those attending were: Sen\nators Byrd, Virginia: Connally. Texas:\nO\u2019Mahoney, Wyoming, and former\nSenator Moore, New Jersey.\nBut more than halt of the Demo- I\ncratio senators were absent, includ\ning not only court bill foes, but such\nparty stalwarts as Harrison of Mis\nsissippi and Byrnes of South Carolina.\nA few big businessmen were among\nthose listening at the dinner- \u2014Vincent\nBendix, M. L. Benedum and Walter\nP. Chrysler.\nThe President was introduced to\nthe diners in Washington by Demo\ncratic Chairman Farley, speaking by\nradio from the banquet, in New York.\nThe chief executive received a full\nminute of applause when he took his\nplace before the microphones.\nMore than a score of times during\nhis 25-minute speech, the President\nwas interrupted by applause, some\ntimes mixed with cheering.\nBiggest Demonstration\nThe biggest demonstration oc\ncurred when he concluded a discus\nsion of utilities by saying that con\ntrol of $13,000,000,000 of securities by\nowners of less than $000,000,000 was\na case of \"a 96-ineh dog being;\nwagged by a four-inch tail.\u201d\nAfter the crowd concluded its\ndemonstration, the President con\ntinued chuckling for a moment, and\nthen interpolated this comment:\n\u2019\u2019lf you work that out in feet nnd\ninches it is amazing. Think of the\npower in that four inches!\"\nThe chief executive omitted two\nparagraphs of his prepared text in\norder to finish speaking within the\nallotted radio time. One was a para\ngraph lauding Andrew Jackson \"for\nhis unending contribution to the\nvitality of our democracy.\" The other\nwas an assertion that the source of\nfalse charges against the administra\ntion could lie \"easily located.\u201d\nThe President remained at the ban\nquet after his address to hear other\nspeakers,\nMr Roosevelt reviewed the struggles\nof Jefferson, Jackson. Theodore Roose\nvelt and Woodrow Wilson for what he\ncalled the \"basic morals of democracy.\"\n\"In our nation today,\u201d he continued,\n\"we still have the continuing menace\nof a comparatively small number of\npeople who honestly believe in their\nsuperior right to Influence and direct\ngovernment, and who are unable to\nsee or unwilling to admit that the\npractices by which they maintain their\nprivileges are harmful to the body\npolitic.\n\"In my message to the Congress on\nMonday, I made it. abundantly clear\nthat this administration seeks to\nservo the needs, and to make effective\nthe will, of the overwhelming majority\nof our citizens and seeks to curb\nabuses of power and privilege by small\nminorities.\n\u201cThus, we in tarn are striving to\nuphold the integrity of the morals of\nour democracy.\u201d\nMAGILL HITS LATEST\nROOSEVELT SPEECH\nWashington, Jan. 9 (AP)\u2014Dr\nHugh 8. Magill, president of the\nAmerican Federation of Investors,\nSaid tonight that investors were\n\"further disheartened\u201d by President\nRoosevelt's Jackson day speech.\"\nCiting Mr Roosevelt's reference to\nthe \"evil of utility holding company\ncontrol,\" Magill said In a statement\nthat attacks on the \"entire\" utility\nindustry \u201ccannot be Justified by a\npresumed attack on the holding com-\nRoosevelt Asks Record\nDefense Appropriation\nAsks Congress for $991,300,000 and Also Begins Shap\ning Request for Even Greater Funds\u2014Nt* zy Will\nReceive Special Attention\nWashington, Jan. s\u2014(AP)\u2014Presi\ndent Roosevelt asked Congress today\nfor record peacetime national defense\nappropriations of $991,300,000, and\nsimultaneously began shaping a re\nquest for even greater funds.\nWhile his annual budget message,\nasking nearly a billion dollars for the\narmy and navy in the. 1939 fiscal\nyear, was being read to the Senate\nand House, he conferred at the White\nHouse with legislators and naval of\ncials about a special message asking\na supplemental outlay for a bigger\nnavy.\nBasle Naw Program Hinted\nChairman Taylor (D., Col.) of the\nHouse appropriations committee, one\nof the conferees, said the message\nwould be dispatched \"as soon as con\nvenient.\u201d\nFrom others at the conference\ncame hints the message would ask\na basic new warship building pro\ngram for several years to come, re\nplacing the 1931 Vinson-Trammell act.\nThus the United States would fol\nlow the lead of Great Britain and\nJapan in abandoning the yardstick of\nthe expired Washington and London\nnaval limitation treaties. The pn>-\ngram laid down in the Vinson-Trem\nmell act, was based on the Washing\nton and London treaties.\nThe President\u2019s budget message\nadvised Congress that \u201cworld condi\ntions over which this nation has no\ncontrol\u201d and \u201cfuture events which to\nday cannot definitely be foretold,\u201d\nmight make it necessary for him to\nask additional defense funds.\nPending such action, he recom\nmended allotting $569,827,003 to the\nnavy and $418,796,000 to the army,\nplus emergency funds which would\nswell the defense total to $991,300,-\n000. This total was 98 per cent high\ner than that of the budget five years\nremoved\u2014l 934.\nWould Lay 22 New Keels\nThe budget provided for a start\nduring the fiscal year opening July\n1 on the construction of two battle\nships, two light cruisers, eight de\nstroyers. six submarines and four\nauxiliary vessels in addition to 70\ncraft, including two battleships, al\nreading building or contracted for.\nFunds for other ships proposed by\nthe President would be provided in a\ndeficiency appropriation later this ses\nsion. Representative Taylor said. He\npromised prompt consideration for both\nthe budget and supplementary re\nquests.\nThough the President's conferees\nsaid no decision was reached on types\nand numbers of additional vessels.\nAdmiral William D. Leahy, chief of\noperations, indicated the navy fa\nvored one or more battleships beyond\nthe four building or projected, two\naircraft carriers, and numerous small\ncruisers.\nThe others called to the White\nHouse for the conference were Charles\nEdison, the navy\u2019s assistant secre\ntary; Chairman Vinson (D., Ga.) of\nthe House naval committee and\nChairman Umstead (D., N. C.) of the\nHouse naval appropriations subcom\ncommittee.\nShore and Island Defenses\nSignificant of the times was the\nprovision made in the budget for\nstrengthening defenses in .continental\nUnited States, in Panama and Ha\nwaii.\nNo mention was made of the island\nof Guam, fortification of which was\nforbidden under the nine-power treaty,\nnow denounced by Japan.\nDuring the fiscal year 1939. begin\nning July 1 of this year, two battle\nships, two light cruisers, eight de\nstroyers, six submarines and four\nauxiliary vessels are to be built.\nArmy Increases Proposed\nIncreases to the army provided\nprincipally for augmenting the per\nsonnel of the regular army, National\nguard and reserve.\nProvision was made for increasing\nthe number of regular army officers\nby 112 to reach 12,485. which is still\n2174 short of the war department's\nobjective of 14,659.\nThe budget, provided for the same\nnumber of enlisted men\u2014l62,oo0 \u2014as\nin 1938, but an increase in the Na\ntional guard from 200,000 to 205,000,\nwhich is still short of the objective,\n210.000.\nThe estimates included funds for\ntraining 25,530 reserve officers for 14\ndays each.\nThe budget called for increases In\nnavy personnel \u201cchiefly required to\nman the increased number of ships\nand planes that will be in operation\nduring 1939, and to Increase the\nstrength of the fleet marine force.\"\nThe goal is 110,570 enlisted navy men\nby the end of 1939, an increase of\n5570 during that year.\nThe marine corps will he enlarged\nby 1000 men until, at the end of the\nyear, it numbers 18.000.\nAir Force Growth Emphasised\nThe importance acquired by the\narmy air corps was seen in the fact\nHull Reciprocal Trade Pacts\nBig Benefit, Officials Say\nWashington. Jan. 8 (AP) Ths\nstate department credited a portion ot\nthe $1,499,566,000 increase in Amer\nica's foreign commerce in the first\n11 months of 1937 to Secretary Hull's\nreciprocal, trade policy today.\n\"There are definite indications that\nIhe trade agreements program is\nhelping to promote mutually beneficial\ntrade between the United States and\nother countries,\" the department said.\nObserving that It was not possible\nto separate completely the factors\ncontributing to the general Increase,\nthe department added: \"It Is signifi\ncant not only that our exports have\ngained relatively more to the agree\nment countries as a group than to\nnonagreement countries but also that\nimports of American products into the\nagreement countries have generally in\ncreased more than have imports of the\nproducts of other countries.\n\"In otner words, the relative posi\ntion of the United Slates In these\nmarkets has Improved.\"\nThis country now is preparing to\nnegotiate a commercial pact with the\nUnited Kingdom\u2014a project regarded\nns the most Important in Secretary\nHull\u2019s program to expand Interna\ntional trade by breaking down tariff\nharriers.\nStatistics made public by the de\npartment showed that the total two\nway trade with the 14 nations with\nwhich agreements were in effect dur\ning all of 1936 rone from $1,719,830,000\nIn the first II months of 1936 to $2.-\n262.517.000 In the same period of 1937,\nan Increase of 31.5 per cent.\nTrade with nil other countries In\ncreased 35.5 per cent during the same\nperiod\u2014from $2,784,278,000 to $3,639.-\n557.000. Exports to trade agreement\ncountries expanded from $799,336,000\nin the first 11 months of 1936 to sl.-\n1404137.000 tor the same period of\n1937. nr 42.6 per cent; while those to\nall other countries ^creased from sl.*\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, JANUARY 13, 1938\nthat almost exactly one-third of the\nwar department budget was absorbed\nby the air force. The estimate was\napproximately $140,000,000 (including\nindirect, charges such as pay, cloth\ning. rations, housing and transporta\ntion) and was about 15 per cent\nhigher than the current year.\nThe war department stated it de\nsired to reach the quota of 2320 air\nplanes set. by the \u201cBaker hoard.\u201d\nFormer Secretary of War Newton\nD. Baker, who died recently, presided\nover the board in 1934.\nMotorization of the army will pro\nceed apace under the 1939 budget, the\nwar 4wepartment commented, \u201cthere\nwill be a continuation of the mod\nernizatiGP, mechanization and motor\nization programs for field artillery,\nantiaircraft, infantry and cavalry\nunits.\"\nPublic works estimates for war de\npartment construction included proj\nects for the air corps technical school\nat Chanute field. Illinois, and for one\nestablished recently at. Denver; for\nprojects at Fort. Knox. Ky., Fort\nBenning. Ga., and for ordnance corps\ndepots al Savanna, 111., and Camp\nStanley, Tex.\nFRANK ACCEPTS\nTASK OF GUIDING\nG.O.P. PROGRAM\nPlans \u2018Open-Minded\u2019 Search\nfor Policies to Keep Amer\nica \u2018Going Concern\u2019 and\nInsure \u2018Congenial Life\u2019\nWashington, Jan. 6\u2014(AP) \u2014Glenn\nFrank accepted the chairmanship of\nthe Republican party\u2019s program\ncommittee tonight and promised to\nI conduct an \u201copen-minded\u201d search for\nI policies that \u201cwill keep America a\nI going concern.\u201d\nThe aim, he said, will be to de\ntermine lines of national action\nI which will \u201cinsure a way of life\ncongenial to the American spirit.\u201d\nThe \u201cfull resources of intelligence,\u201d\nhe said, are needed to cope with \u201cex\ntraordinarily grave social and eco\nnomic difficulties.\u201d.\n\u201cHigh Purpose\u201d Praised\nThe former president of the Univer\nsity of Wisconsin was chosen last\nmonth by the Republican executive\ncommittee to direct more than 100\nleaders in drafting a declaration of\nprinciples.\nChairman John Hamilton of the Re\npublican national committee wired\ni Frank praising the \u201chigh purpose\"\nwith which he accepted.\nFlank's telegram of acceptance fol\nlows:\n\u201cI could not until today give you,\nas I now give you. my assured accept-\nI ance of the chairmanship nt the spe\ncial commission of political and eco\ni nomic inquiry created by the Republi\ncan national committee.\n\"No one. either before the St Louis\n1 meeting or during its sessions, com\nmunicated with me, regarding this\nchairmanship. I am glad this was so\nbecause it leaves me free now to ac\ncept this post without any prior obli\ngation to any Individual or to any\ngroup In the party. It meant, how\never, that, when notified of the com\nmittees action, I was not in position\nto assume a major obligation of this\nsort until I had made the necessary\nreadjustments in my other obligations.\nThat alone accounts for this delayed\nacceptance.\nNot to Write Platform\n\"Along with my acceptance, let me\nexpress my understanding of the na\nture and purpose of this special com\nmission.\n\"It is not the business of this com\nmission to write platforms for the\n1938 and 1940 campaigns. That is a\nmatter for state conventions and those\nwho are to stand for election in the\nI midterm campaigns of 1938 and for\nthe national convention preceding the\nI 1940 campaign. The sole legal source\nI of party policy is the national conven\ni tion and the custodians of party policy\nin the interims between national con\nventions are the Republican members\nj in the Senate and the House when, as\nI now, the party is not In power.\n\"It Is not the business of this com\ni mission to promote the candidacy of\nI anybody for any office.\n426,811.009 to $1,886,645,000. or 32.2\nper cent.\nImports from trade agreement coun\ntries amounted to $919,994,000 in the\n1936 per iod compared with $1,122,290.-\n000, a rise hf 22 per cent; while from\nall other countries the Import in\ncrease was 39 4 per cent from $1,257,-\n4,17,000 to $1,752,912,000.\nEND OF \u2018ROBINSON\u2019\nMYSTERY SOUGHT\nWashington, Jan. 5 (AR) Identi\nfication of the mysterious Mrs Donald\nL. Robinson, missing In Soviet Rus\nsia. as an American citizen\u2014Mrs\nRuth Marie Rubens of New York.\u2014\nmoused the state department today to\npress for a complete solution of the\nmonth-old case.\nSecretary Hull prepared Io address\nfurther demands to the Soviet gov\nernment, through the emlia*sy In\nMoscow, for Information on the wom\nan's whereabouts and the status of\nher cnse.\nOfficial* Indicated he nl\u00bbo was\nready to demand her release. If she\nIs under arrest and circumstances\njustify hl* request.\nMother Told of \u201cRelease\u201d\nMiami, Fla.. .Inn. \u00ab\u2014(AP)\u2014Mt*\nFrederick G. Boerger said today she\nhad received a telegram from\ndaughter In New York stating that\nMi* Adolph Arnold Rubens, also her\ndaughter, had been released at Mos\ncow where she had been detained' by\nSoviet authorities ns \u201cMrs Donald U\nRobinson.\" Mr* Boerger said the\ndaughter in New York. Mis* Connie\nBoerger, did not state the source ot\nher Information or whether Mi* Ru\nbens'* husband had been released.\nF. D. R. DEMANDS\nCUT IN SPENDING\nOF $539,000,000\nEstimates Deficit May Be a\nBillion and Warns It May\nBe Increased by Foreign\nCrises and Relief Needs\nWashington, Jan. 5 (AP)\nPresident Roosevelt sent to Congress\ntoday a budget calling for a $539,-\n000,000 cut in government spend\ning next fiscal year, but estimated\nthat nevertheless there would be a\nbillion-dollar deficit.\nAt the same time he gave notice\nthat because of two grave uncer\ntainties\u2014foreign troubles and the\nrelief needs of the unemployed\u2014the\ndeficit may be even greater.\nCongress received Ihe message wilh\nmixed comment. Some said there\nshould be greater cuts in spending.\nOthers objected to some recommended\ncuts.\nChairman O'Connor (D\u201e N. Y.) of\nthe House rules committee said he\nregretted \"very much to see this ir\nreducible minimum of a requirement\nof about $7,000,000,000\" for federal ex\npenses.\nMr Roosevelt's estimate of total ex\npenditures was $6,869,000,000, com\npared with estimated expenditures for\nthis year, closing next June 30, of\n$7,408,000,000.\nHe estimated revenues for the 1939\nyear would be $.'1,919,000,000 compared\nwith an estimate of $6,279,000,000 for\nthis year.\nThe greater part of the proposed\ncut in spending was accounted for by\nthe total suggested for relief. The\nbudget figure was $1,266,000,000 as\nagainst $1,759,000,000 this year.\nFailure of Mr Roosevelt's figures\nto allow all that some had hoped for\nfarm benefits brought quick protests.\nEntirely Inadequate. Says McGill\nNoting that the budget called for\na $330,000,000 direct appropriation for\nsoil conservation payments and use\nof $110,000,000 of other funds for this\npurpose. Senator McGill (D.. Kan.),\ncoauthor with Senator Pope (D.. Ida.)\nof the Senate farm bill, commented:\n\"The sum is entirely inadequate. It\nhas been our understanding all along\nthat we could count on $500,000,000.\ni Surely the Congress will insist on it.\"\n\"We must have at least $500,000,-\ni 000.\" Pope said.\nThere were many general comments\nof approval, however, such as that\nof Senator Sheppard (D\u201e Tex.) who\nsaid the budget was \"an honest and\nlogical effort to bring expenditures\nand income into balance at the earli\nest. possible date.\u201d\nSenator Minton (D.. Ind.) applaud\ned as \u201cwise\" the president\u2019s leaving\nthe way open for. supplemental re\nlief and naval estimates.\nSeveral indicated they could not\nagree to the President\u2019s proposed\nhalving of the present $280,000,000\nfor public roads.\nChairman McKellar (D.. Tenn.) ot\nthe Senate roads committee said he\nbelieved road appropriations could be\n\u201creduced some.\"\n\u201cThe message.\" he added, \"was a\nsplendid step forward towards re\nduced expenditures. Congress, where\never it can, ought to add to those re\nductions.\"\nStrikes G. O. P. Criticism Note\nRepresentative Rich (R-, Pa.)\nstruck the general note of Republican\ncriticism when he commented: \"The\nbudget present* a deplorable situa\ntion.\"\nRepresentative Fish (R., N. Y.)\nsaid: \"It doesn't make any difference\nany longer what the President says\nin his budget messages. Why should\nanyone believe in them?\u201d\nAt almost the same time his mes\nsage was being read to the Senate\nand House, the President began a\nconference with high naval officials\nand legislative leaders on a message\nhe proposes to send Congress, asking\nsupplemental naval appropriations.\nThose attending the conference\nhinted afterwards that the President\nhad In mind scrapping the present\nVinson-Trammell naval bill, based on\nthe Washington and London naval\ntreaties, and asking a far larger navy\nthan Congress now has authorized.\nIn telling Congress he might find\nit necessary to ask additional sums\nfor relief and national defense the\nPresident said:\u2014\nSoutheastern Governors\nFavor Wage-Hour Limits\nWashington, Jan. 7 \u2014(AP) \u2014Pros-\npects for federal wage and hour legis\nlation apparently improved today\nwhen the southeastern governor*\u2019 con\nference indorsed the idea and some\nsouthern congressmen suggested they\nmight accept a substitute for the ad\nministration'* bill.\nAfter a luncheon with President\nRoosevelt, the governors' conference\nIndorsed the principle of establishing\n\"a floor for wages and ceiling for\nhours\" It also expressed confidence\nthat Congress and the President would\nwork out satisfactory legislation.\nThe conference was attended by the\ngovernor* of Alabama, Georgia. Flor\nida. Louisiana. Tennessee. North Car\nolina and South Carolina.\nIt* action aroused wide-spread in\nterest in view of the fact that south\nern congressmen were a major ele\nment in the House opposition that\nsidetracked the administration's wage\nhour bill at the recent special session.\nRepresentative Dies (D., Tex.), one\nof the leader* of the group which\nshunted the legislation back to the\nHouse labor committee, revealed that\na few member* had started drafting\na substitute.\nDewey Intercedes for Robber\nHe Says \u2018Lived a Hopeless Life'\nNew York. Jan. 4\u2014Thoms* E. Dew\ney, relentless prosecutor of New Yorks\nracket gangsters, went Into court\nagain today, but this time on an er\nrand of mercy.\nDewey, who ha* just taken office\nas district-attorney of New York\ncounty, appeared before Judge Morris\nKoenig who was ready to pronounce\na sentence of 10 to 20 years In prison\non Charles Galonte. 24.\n\"Your honor.\" Dewey said. \u201d1\nwould like to \u00bbay a few words about\nthis boy.\nThe fighting prosecutor's voice was\ngentle.\n\u201cGalenta,\" he said, \u201cwas an orphan\nat two year* of age Both parents\ndied. He has lived a hopeless\nlife. There was no one to guide\nhim. Ths report shows that when\never he couW find a Job he took\nHOUSE TO RUSH\nNAVY ADDITIONS\nASKED BY F.D.R.\nSpecial Measure Will Be\nShoved Ahead of Tax Re\nvision Work \u2014White House\nMessage Awaited\nWashington, Jan. 9 (AP)\nInsiders said today that House\nleaders intend to rush through ad\nministration legislation authorizing\na bigger navy before Congress\ntackles the pressing question of\ncorporate tax revision.\nTax committee members had set\nSaturday originally as the date\nwhen their measure would be ready\nfor House consideration. However,\nwell-informed persons predicted that\nPresident Roosevelt would send Con\ngress a special message within the\nnext few days urging immediate\nauthorization of naval expansion be\nyond that already approved.\nDefense Seen Necessary\nThia action would be in line with\na recent statement by Chairman Tay\nlar (D.. Col.), of the House appropria\ntions committee, regarding the Presi\ndent's views. Taylor said Mr Roose\nvelt believed it would be the \"bight\nof unwisdom\" for the United States\n\"to fail to show the world at. this\ntime that we are going to prepare to\ndefend ourselves.\u201d\nSome leaders expressed belief that\nthe naval legislation could he disposed\nof in the House within two or three\ndays, and that it would not delay tax\nrevision materially.\nThe bill would not provide actual\nfunds for the vessels it authorized,\nthey said. The question of financing\na start on the new program could be\ndecided later in the session.\nSeveral members said details of the\nproposed bill probably would not be\nknown until Chairman Vinson\n(D., Ga.), of the House naval com\nmittee. conferred with the President.\nBut they concurred in a forecast by\nTaylor that it would embrace \"a\nstrong, horizontal enlargement.\"\nNaval committeemen called atten\ntion to the fact, that, while several\nadditional battleships of the $60,000,000\nclass could be constructed without\nnew authorization legislation. Con\ngress would have to increase the\nauthorizations of Jhe Vinson-Trammell\nact before more heavy cruisers or\naircraft carriers could be constructed.\nTwo battleships are under construc\ntion at the Brooklyn and Philadelphia\nnavy yards, and the President already\nhas asked Congress for funds to start\ntwo more in the coming fiscal year.\n63 Ships May Be Built\nFor U. S. Foreign Trade\nWashington. Jan. 9 (AP)\u2014The\nMaritime commission announced to\nday that seven shipping companies\nhad agreed to build from 29 to 43\nships for use in the foreign trade\nwithin the next four years. In return^\nIhe commission approved long-term\noperaiing subsidies, agregating $7,-\n359,000 annually, for the lines.\nSimilar agreements now being\nnegotiated with other companies may\nbring to 63 the number ot ships to\nbe considered with the aid of federal\nsubsidies, the commission said.\nThe seven companies receiving long\nterm contracts agreed to build 20\nvessels by 1912, starting 14 of them\nthis year. The commission said it\nalso required these companies to de\nvelop plans for 23 additional ships.\nChairman Joseph P. Kennedy esti\nmated it. would cost $119,000,000 to\nbuild all the vessels covered by\ndefinite agreements or merely pro\nposed. The commission also an\nnounced that short-term contracts had\nbeen made with six companies \"pend\ning a further study of their problems.\"\nCleveland. Jan. 9\u2014(AP)\u2014A move\nment to buttress national air defense\nby coordinating the activity of every\naviation group in the country was\nput under way here today.\nCalled the first national aeronautic\nplanning conference, a meeting at\ntended by aircraft manufacturers,\nstate and government officials and\nprivate flying groups discussed, among\nI other topics, the problem of the\nUnited States catching up with Europe\nIn the field of civilian flying.\nHe declined to say what form the\nnew mesaure would take, hut Repre\nsentative Mc\u00dfeynolds (D.. Tenn.)\nsuggested it might be restricted to a\nfew industries.\n\u2018The farm bill was designed to\napply only to a few commodities like\ncorn, wheat and cotton.\" he said, \"so\nif It's constitutional to do that with\nagriculture, it would be constitutional\nto legislate for part* of industry.\"\nMc\u00dfeynolds did not specify the in\ndustries to which the legislation would\napply, but conceded that textiles\nmight be one.\nAnother feature of the farm legisla\ntion which he said might well be in\ncluded in the labor bill was the pro\nvision for a referendum before the\nmeasure could become operative. By\nthis means, a majority nf operators\nIn any Industry would determine\nwhether their wage and hour stand\nards would he subject to federal regu\nlation.\nDies said his group wanted a com\npromise \"satisfactory to both sides.\"\nand that any measure It drafted would\nnot be brought to the House floor\nuntil the President approved It.\nit. He worked pretty hard for a\nbov ot hi* year*.\nGalente had pleaded guilty to first\ndegree robbery. This, Dewey said, was\n\"an outrage.\" He asked the court'*\npermission to withdraw the plea and\nhave Galenie plead guilty to grand\nlarceny in th* second degree\nThe court agreed. The youth stared\nIn amazement. A sentence ot two and\na half to five rears In prison was pro\nnounced, which means Galente can\nget out In 20 month* on good be\nharlor.\nJudge Koenig commented:\n\"1 commendr the humanitarian at\ntitude ot the district-attorney. He has\ncertainly given lit* to the cold rigidity\not the law.\"\nGalente was arreated in a $2.50 hold\nup. A companlM was sentenced to\nthree year* on a plea ot guilty to\nmisdemeanor.\nSutherland's Retirement\nWill Help \u2018Liberal' Group\nRoosevelt Now Has Opportunity to Increase That Fac\ntion in Supreme Court to Dependable Majority\u2014\nReed, Minton Prominently Mentioned\nWashington. Jan. s\u2014(AP)\u2014Associ\nate Justice George Sutherland an\nnounced his retirement from the su\npreme court, today, giving President\nRoosevelt a long-awaited opportunity\nto increase the court's \u201cliberal\" fac\ntion to a dependable majority.\nFour of the remaining member*\u2014\nStone. Brandeis, Cardozo and Black\nhave habitually espoused a liberal in\nterpretation of the constitution, tend\ning to confer wide powers on the fed\neral government, instead of restricting\nthem to the letter of that document.\nNow, one more follower of that\nschool Is expected to be appointed by\nthe President, who has engaged in\nrepeated battles nith the court about\nthe way in which the constitution\nshould be interpreted. This appoint\nment would give the liberal group five\nof the court's nine members. Aside\nfrom these five, Chief Justice Hughes\nand Associate Justice Roberts have\noccasionally supported the liberal and\noccasionally rhe conservative side.\nThey thus held a balance of power,\nwhich, as Washington sees it will\nend with the new appointment.\nOf course, the new alignment would\nKNUDSEN BELIEVES\nEND OF RECESSION\nWILL ARRIVE SOON\nDeclares It Is \u2018Better\u2019 to\nCurtail Work Than Lower\nPrices \u2014Has No Faith in\nRoosevelt\u2019s Plan\nWashington, Jan. 6\u2014(AP)\u2014William\nKnudsen, the president of vast Gen\neral Motors corporation, testified to\nday that in his opinion the present\nbusiness recession would be short\nlived and that his company was mak\ning plans accordingly.\nBut. he said, in response to repeared\nquestions from Chairman Byrnes (D\u201e\nS. C.) of the Senate unemployment\ncommittee, the company's surplus of\n$450,000,000 could not be used to keep\nmen at work and avoid the recent\nlayoff of 30.000 men.\nFor, he added, in times such as\nthese it is \"better\u201d to work off ac\ncumulations of unsold stocks by cur\ntailing production than by adjusting\nprices downward in accordance with\nreduced demand.\nDecries Roosevelt Plan\nIn addition, he made it evident that\n,he thought little good could come\nI from President Roosevelt\u2019s proposal\ni that industry and government get to\ngether periodically to gauge the fu\nture and plan production.\n\"I don\u2019t think anyone in Gods\nworld could have told me that sales\nw\u2019ere going to drop 50 per cent In two\nweeks.\" he said.\nWhat is needed to end the depres\nsion. he emphasized again and again,\nis confidence and. in answer to ques\ntions he said he thought that if Gen\neral Motors would reemploy the 30.-\n000 it laid off. that would do much to\nincrease confidence.\nBut that \"would not be business,\u201d\nhe testified: employment must be ad\njusted to production; \"constant em\nployment cannot be assured unless\nthere is work to do; if the men were\nreemployed there would be nothing\nfor them to work on.\"\nKnudsen, a ruddy-faced giant of a\nman. who worked his way from the\nstatus of a laborer in overalls to that\not an industrial titan, was one of a\nseries of big businessmen, economists\nand statisticians who are giving the\ncommittee their views about the\ncauses of unemployment and remedies\nfor it.\nAffable, but noticeably nervous at\nthe outset, he read a prepared state\nment telling how the depression hit\nGeneral Motors, causing a devastat\ning drop in sales in December. Then\nhe sat back to answer questions, most\nof them relating tn layoffs and the\nbusiness outlook. Later he discussed\nthe situation with President Roose\n-1 velt.\nA total of 46.000.009 man-hours of\nwork were lost because of strikes\nearly in the year, but were completely\nmade up In overtime work later.\nNinety-one per cent of General Mo\ntors dealers, handling 93 per cent of\nthe corporation's output, made a\nprofit, in 1937. Inventories reached a\nrecord high nt $290,000,000 in 1937.\n$50,000,000 Asked of U. S.\nFor Drive Against Liquor\nChicago. Jan 9 \u2014(AP) \u2014A plea for\n\"at least $50,009,000\" for \"dissemina\ntion ot the truth about alcohol and\nintoxicating beverages\u201d was voiced to\nday by the American Business Men's\nResearch foundation in an open let\nter to President Roosevelt and Con\ngress.\nThe letter, aigned by Charles R\nJones, executive vice-president, said\nthe foundation was \"moved by what\nwe are convinced is a national emerg\nency.\u201d\n\u201dW* respectfully call your attention\nto the fact\u201d the letter said, \u201cthat dur\ning the past four years the liquor\ntraffic, by government permission, has\nexpended upward* ot $109,000,000 In\nadvertising and propaganda, attract\ning thereby million* of customers\nwho. in that time have paid mor* than\n$12,000,000,000 to the maker* and re\ntailer* of Intoxicants\nThe foundation asserted the money\nspent for drinks caused \u201cirreparable\nloss to trade retarding desper\nately needed home construction: crip\npling a normal expansion of the auto\nmobile industry: seriously jeopardiz\ning the solution\u2019of the relief prob\nlem. and thus becoming, automatically,\nsuch a significant factor in the pres\nent continuing depression.\u201d\n\u201cThis Whisky Depression\u201d\nThe letter said the $50,900,000 asked\nfor a temperance campaign was les*\nthan 10 per cent of the amount re\nceived yearly by the federal govern\nment from liquor traffre. and approxi\nmated the sum \u201cthe liquor industry\nla expending to increase the rise of\nIntoxicants.\u201d\nIn a memorandum accompanying\nth* letter, the foundation termed the\nbusiness slump \"this whisky depres\nsion\" and concluded:\u2014\n\"All Indication* point to a steadily\nIncreasing nations! coat and loss to\nthe American people through the con\ntinuing liquor traffic, unless con\nstructive steps are taken to meet the\nnot reverse the court\u2019s historic deci-\nsion outlawing the NRA as unconati- I\ntutional. a verdict which touched off i\nthe long administration battle against\nthe courts. The vote in that case was\nunanimous. But it couM reverse th\u00abi\ndecision by which the AAA was in\nvalidated. to Mr Roosevelt\u2019* expressed\nannoyance. That decision was six to\nthree. Among the six were Associate\nJustice Van Devanter, who retired\nlast spring and was replaced by Jus-\ntice Black, and Sutherland.\nIf Black and Sutherland's successor\nvoted for the validation of such legis-\nlation and the others voted as before.\nthe lineup would be five to four in\nfavor of holding it, constitutional In\ncidentally. Hughes and Roberts both I\nsided with the \"conservatives\" in that\ncase.\nWho Will Be Chosen!\nAs always, when an important gov- I\nernmental post becomes vacant, i\nWashington was abuzz tonight with\nI speculation as to who would be ap\npointed. Everyone interested had his i\nlist of possibilities and some of them\nI were lengthy. But several names\nl stood at or near rhe top of each\nThese were Solicitor-General Stan\nley Reed. Senator Sherman Minton of\nIndian^ and former Senator Sam G.\nj Bratton, now a judge of the 10th cir\ncult court of appeals. These three\nwere known to have been among\nI those under consideration when Black\nwas appointed last year.\nOther names mentioned included:\nRobert H. Jackson, assistant attorney\ngeneral; Felix Frankfurter and James\nM. l^ndis ot the Harvard Law school;\nSenator Wagner (D.. N. Y.) and Fer\ndinand Pecora. a judge ot the New\ni York state supreme court.\nSutherland, for years a bulwark of\nthe court'* dwindling conservative\nbloc, announced hi* retirement at a\nbrief press conference in hi* cham\nbers ar the court building. Affable\nand apparently well pleased, he\nhanded reporters a brief letter ad\ndressed to President Roosevelt.\n\"Having reached the age of more\nthan 75 years, and having held my\ncommission as associate justice of\nthe supreme court of the United\nStates, and served in that court for\n15 years and thus being eligrible for\nretirement under the Sumners act\nof March 1, 1937. entitled 'an act for\nthe retirement of justices of the su\npreme court.* I desire to avail my\nself of the right, privileges and judi\ncial service specified in that act, and\nto that end. I hereby retire from\nregular active service on the bench,\nthis retirement to be effective on and\nafter Tuesday, the eighteenth of Jan\nuary, 1938.\"\nAmong the \u201crights and privileges\u2019\nto which he referred is a guaranteed\nincome of $20,000 annually for the\nrest of his days. The Sumners act,\npermitting retirement at full pay.\nwas passed, some said, to encourage\nolder judges to leave the bench.\nThe judicial t service of which he\nspoke, is the privilege of serving from\ntime to time in the lo#er courts, if\nhe chooses to do so. Justice Van De\nvanter. who retired under similar\nconditions, is now performing such\n\u25a0ervice.\nBern tn England\nSutherland, whose small wiry figure\nand pointed, steely gray beard was a\nfamiliar sight on the bench, was one\nlof the few supreme court Judges\nI born in a foreign land. He was a\nnative of England, bur bi* parent*\nI emigrated to the United States when\nhe was 15 months old.\nThey moved on to Utah and Suth\nerland's rearing was in the pioneering\nenvironment of the West in the sixties\nand seventies. After studying law. and\npracticing with distinction, he became\na member of Utah* first legislature,\nserved later in the national House of\nRepresentatives and in 1905 was elect\ned to the Senate. He served two terms,\nand then was defeated by the incum\nbent Senator King, a Democrat and\nhis former law partner.\nNevertheless. Sutherland was a\npowerful figure in the Repullcan poli\ntics in his state and was generally\ncredited with swinging Utah to Wil\nliam Howard Taft in 1912. It was one\nof only two states which Taft carried.\nPresident Harding appointed him to\nthe court in 1922. and his service on\nihe bench was notable for an unvary\ning belief in rhe wisdom and inviola\nbility of the letter of th* constitution.\n\"Whether the legislation under re\nview is wise or unwise is a matte\nwith which we have nothing to do.\u201d\nhe said in one ot his opinions, \"the\nonly legitimate inquiry we can make\nis whether it is constitutional If it\nis nor. its virtues, if it have any. can\nnot save it; if tt i*. its faults cannot\nbe invoked to accomplish it* destruc\ntion, If the provisions of the con\nstitution be not upheld when they\npinch a* well as when they comfort,\nthey may well be abandoned.\"\nproblems presented.\u201d\nThe memorandum detailed the\nt foundation's estimate of the costs of j\nI liquor traffic between April. 1933. and I\nOctober, 1937, placing th* total \u00abt\n$15,690,790,869.\ni The foundation is incorporated not i\nI for profit. It is headed by Frank K\nGannett. Rochester. N. V. publisher:\nof the Gannett newspaper*\nDrunken Pedestrians Said\nChief Peril On Highways\nBoston. Jan. 9\u2014(API-Drunken\nt pedestrians, a Harvard university re-!\nsearch investigator declared today.\n\u201care an even greater source of fa-\ntalitle* on the highway* than drunken\nI driver*.\u201d\nThe sssertlon was made by Dr\nHarry R. DeSllva. head of the motor i\nvehicle driving section of the univer\nsity's bureau of traffic research in I\ndiscussing \u201cMen. motor csrs nnd al\ncohol\" In a public lecture at th* Har- i\nvard medical school.\nDr DeSilva sited \u201cchapter and\nver**\u201d to back his conclusions, some\nof which war*:\n'The past year promise* to bring\nthe total of automobile fatalities to\na new record of 40.090 (previously it\nhas been in the 30.000'*.)\n\"We can be assured that the per\ncentage of accidents associated with\nalcdhol is probably nearer 25 per cent\nthan 10 per cent.\nTt would he Ideal If we could legis\nlate Intoxicated drivers and pedes\ntrians off the road.\n\"The false sense of security which\nalcohol engenders Is by tar th* most\nimportant hizard\"\nDr DeSilva advocated Increasing\nthe \"legal responsibility\" ot persons\ncombining drinking and driving and\nthe citation of facta, not precepts\nabout the dangers ot driving after\nI even a small di Otk-\"\n7\nNATIONAL NEWS\nCOLONIAL EMPIRE\nTO BE INCLUDED IN\nPROPOSED ACCORD\nBritish Experts to Sail About\nFebruary I for Washing\nton \u2014Affected N. E. Prod\nucts Listed\nWashington, Jan. 7 (AP) \u2014The\nUnited States and Great Britain\ncook a seven-league step toward\neconomic cooperation today by an\nnouncing formal \u201cintention to nego\ntiate\" trade agreement.\nSecretary of State Hull\u2019s an\nnouncement disclosed that the Brit\nish colonial empire and Newfound\nland are to be included in the ae\ncord. Excluded are the dominions,\nIreland and India.\nHearings t* Open Marell 14\nMarch 14 was set for the beginning\nnt public hearings on imports and ex\nports suggested tor inclusion. Hull\npublished a 47-page list of over 1009\nimport* on which tariff concessions\nmay he granted.\nFebruary 19 was fixed a* th* clos\ning date for the submission ot brief*\niby importer*, exporter*, producers or\nmanufacturer*, and for applications\nto be heard at the public meetings.\nSecretary Hull said a British dele\ngation of trade experts would Mail\nfrom Britain around the first nt\nFebruary for the United States r<\u00bb\nbegin discussions with United States\nexpert*.\nA list ot export* on which Britain\nmay grant tariff concessions was not\nissued here. This was left, to the\nBritish government to give out.\nA similar announcement is expected\nshortly with regard to a new trad*\nagreement, with Canada. A state de\npartment official said it was believed\nSouth Africa and later A ustralia would\nfollow.\nConcessions up to 50 per rent re\nduction in tariff duties may be\ngranted on British imports into this\ncountry. Other concession* may be\nmade by \"binding\" tariffs at existing\nrates or \"binding\u201d on the free list\nthose products already there.\nThe trade agreement with Great\nBritain, if successfully completed, may\nbe rega-ded as the climax of Secre\ntary Hull\u2019s economic program. The\nUnited Kingdom absorbed $440,122.-\n090 worth of United States exports in\n1934 and sold us $290,335,000 worth of\ngoods.\nOur exports to Britain constituted\nIS per cent of our total to all coun\ntries. and our imports 8 per cent of\nTh\u00bb total 'rom al! countries.\nUnited States export* to the Brit\nish colonial empire (excluding India\nbur including Newfoundland) in 193 g\nwere $49 OOn.oflo. Import* (chiefly\nof essential raw materials) were $230,-\n009.090.\nList of Colonies I Bristled\nSecretary Hull issued a list of th*\nBritish colonies included in the ne\ngotiations (in addition to Newfound\nland). They literally take the nego\ntiator around the world.\nIn Africa they are Kenya. Uganda.\nTanganyika. Nyasaland. northern Rho\ndesia. Zanizihar. British Somaliland.\nNigeria. Gold Coast including Tngoland\nterritory. Sierra Leone, Gambia. St\nHelena Ascension.\nIn the Mediterranean they are Gl\nhraltar. Malta. Cyprus. Palestine (in\neluding the trans-Jordan mandated\nterritories!.\nIn the East they \u00abre Ceylon. Strait*\nsettlements. Federated Malay states.\nJohore. Kedah. Kelantan. Trengeanu,\nNorth Borneo, Brunei. Sarawak Hong\nKong. Mauritius. Aden. Seychelles.\nTn the Pacific they are: Fiji Gil\nbert and Ellice Islands. British Solo\nmon islands and Tonga.\nIn the West Indies and elsewhere\nthey are: The Bahamas. Barbados.\nBritish Guiana. British Honduras. Js\nmaica. Gayman islands. Turks and\nCaicos islands. Leeward islands. Trin\nidad and Tabago. Windward island*.\nFalkland islnd*.\nSome of the Imports 4 f fee ted\nSecretary Hull* long list ot im\nports on which concessions may be\nconsidered included:\nWhisky, boots and shoes, wool**\nfabrics, cotton fabric*, dove*, leather\ngoods, saddlery and harness, hard\nware. certain pickled and salt fish.\nvarious manufactured and chemical\nproduct*, ale. porter, stout, beer,\ndressed furs and many other products.\nThe announcement of intention to\nnegotiate definitely starts the Anglo-\nAmerican negotiations on their way.\nFirst intimation that they were con\nsidered was on November I? when\nSecretary Hull issued his announce\nment nt \"contemplation\" of a trad*\na greement.\nAffected N. E. Products\nProve Extensive List\nWashington. Jan. 7 Among the\nproducts manufactured in New Eng\nland on which it is proposed that\ntariffs may be revised downward\nI under the proposed British trade\nag -\u201cement are the following;\u2014\nAll medicinal preparations which\nnow have tariff protection of ftom tS\nto 25 cents, cellulose and cellulose\nacetate preparations and compounds,\nwhich now enjoy a tariff of 59 cent*\na pound, fish oils, which have a th\nper cent duty, extracts, dyeing and\ntanning compounds, and flavoring ex\ntracts. ink* of all descriptions, wool\ngrease ot all grades, paints of every\nkind, from house paint to colors in\npaint boxes for children, soaps and\nall the product* used in the making\nof conp. brick, clay, and quarry tile,\nelectrical supplies ot all kinds includ\ning electrodes, generator brushes and\nthe like.\nAlso biological chemical metallur\ngical. pharmaceutical sod surgical\narticles and utensils of ell kinds In\ni eluding all scientific article* and\nI utensils. These now enjoy s tariff\n1 protection of 5\u00ab per cent. Wire rop*.\nwhich has tariff protection of 33 per\nI cent, table and s'lverware. buckle*\nand buttons ot all kinds, pins and\nnotion*, knives and cutlery ot all de\nscription*. razor* and safety razor\nblades, shotguns and rifles valued at\nmore than SSO. nautical instrument*\nlot every dc\u00bbcription. textile machinery.\nfinished or unfinished which now ha*\nI tariff protection of 40 per cent.\nAl\u00bbo cordage machines and tobacco\nmanufacturing machine*, bottle cap*\nof metal tennis racquet* anti badmin\nton racquet frame*, molasse* and\nsugar sirups, fish, pickled or salted,\nincluding cod. haddock, hake, pollwk.\ncusk. herring and fish pastes, blue\nberries. cider, vinegar and all Jtllies,\nJanis, marmalades and fruit butters,\nalcoholic beverages ot all kinds.\nAlso cotton yarn, cotton cloth\nbleached and unbleached, cotton\nprUits. mixed cotton and wool, filled\nor coated cotton cloth, waterproof\ncloth, twill back velveteen*, sheetsand\npillow case*, spindle banding, boot and\nshoe lacings, belts and belting for ma\nchinery. rop* for textile machinery,\nhandkerchiefs and woven mufflon.\nclothing and article* ot wearing ap\nparel of *iery description mafic of\ncotton, taco curtain* and ladder tapes.","height":"25947","width":"19870"}}
